==Old English==

===Etymology===
From West Germanic ''*wunjō-'', from Indo-European ''*wen-, *wenə-'' ‘strive for, wish, desire’.  Cognate with Old Saxon [[wunnia]], Old High German [[wunna]] (German [[Wonne]]).  Related to Old English [[wine#Old English|wine]], [[wenian]].  The IE root is also the source of Latin [[venus]], Celtic ''*wenja-'' (Old Irish [[fine]], Welsh [[gwen]]).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /wynn/

===Noun===
'''wynn''' ''f'' (''acc'' '''wynn''' or '''wynne''')
# [[joy]], [[delight]]
# the runic character ᚹ or its manuscript equivalent Ƿ, ƿ (/w/).

